The paper deals with the problem of recovering a sparse signal from underdetermined linear equations, which is a common problem in signal processing and information theory. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.SP (Signal Processing) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also proposes a new algorithm for sparse recovery, which involves optimization and statistical analysis, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a likely sub-category as well. Additionally, the paper uses a Grassman angle approach, which is a technique commonly used in numerical analysis and optimization, making cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with prior information about the probability of each entry of the unknown signal being nonzero, which is a topic related to probabilistic modeling and inference, making cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) a possible sub-category as well.
